Volume 3 of the songwriter tapes is out and I’m just so thankful I got to be part of this project with @lukerobert and @thebarrydean. We had such a great time supporting and pushing each other through these recordings.  Watching a song find its homeland in the writer is one of my favorite parts of writers rounds and the time in the studio making these “tapes” felt like a beautiful expansion of those dark-venue-intimate-moments.  Luke and Barry will always be two of my favorite writers, singers, and poets.  They are family to me.  I think Barry’s version of “If I Had Known” is a fitting chapter-ending to this project.  If I had know how beautiful and difficult anything to do with music would be I’d still do it all again.  Over and over.  Thanks for indulging us writers in our songs.  It’s a blessing to stand on this side of them!

The music video for “Killing Me” comes out on Wednesday, June 7th at 11am CT. I wrote this song with Luke Laird and Hillary Lindsey, two of the greatest songwriters of all time. The idea started with a relationship and then reached into the thoughts we tell ourselves. That self talk - that rattle in our heads usually with something negative to say. I loved the idea of the joyful side of my mind telling the constant critic in there to just hush. Just hush. When it was time for Derrick Javon to bring it all to life he imagined me confronting my younger self with all this. Another layer. Beautifully shot and directed by Derrick and his team and so honestly, joyfully and emotionally executed by Lauren Starr. It was a thrill to watch this group of creators breathe so many new layers into this lyric. I’m so excited to share this video with you.

Losing someone you love is impossibly hard.  I believe the only way to move forward in grief is to keep the people we’ve lost right with us. Right in our chest. Dustin Christensen, Jessie Jo Dillon and I wrote this song about losing someone, about keeping them in a different way, and about hoping they keep us too. TTIY🩵 Out Next Friday, June 9th.
“Killing Me” music video out tomorrow, June 7th at 11am CT 🩵

Very excited for this video to be out in the world today. Derrick and his team did an incredible job bringing this side of these lyrics to life. And I hope all of us (maybe everyone?) experiencing negative self-talk can treat ourselves a little kinder today!!

Happy Children: I heard someone say this once, “I wish you happy children”. Feels like the greatest wish of all time. This song was happily written with my son Chris McKenna. It went through a couple different variations until Dave Cobb brought it so beautifully to life in the studio with the band. If my heart could say just one thing, this song what it would say. We were likely shooting photos around the release of Bittertown in a field across the street from our first little house.
If you only get one thing that’s a given - I hope you have happy children.

Thrilled to announce these shows with my pal @thebrandyclark she is one of my favorite singer/songwriters of all time and one of the very best humans I know. We’ll be trading songs and stories (probably laughs and even tears) and visiting some places I don’t get to play very often. I hope you can join us.

Self-deprecating even as she hoovers up awards and chart-toppers, Lori Mckenna’s been the go-to songsmith for everyone from Taylor Swift and Chris Stapleton to Little Big Town and Maren Morris – sometimes writing solo and sometimes as one third of the Love Junkies, with pals Liz Rose and Hillary Lindsey. 
 
But right now the singer-songwriter and hit-maker is packing up to go on tour with her own album, 1988 💿
 
We caught up with her to discuss writing with family, the role of AI in songwriting and the stories behind the songs on 1988 📻
 
Read our conversation, straight from her music room in her home near Boston, Massachusetts, at the link in bio.

Been waiting a long time for the release of this newest Tim McGraw record! I got to work with Tim and the brilliant @bobminner on “Nashville CA/L.A. Tennessee” and @chasemcgillsongwriter and @parkerwellingnohe on “Letter From Heaven” both songs came from such a deep well of different emotions. It is never lost on me how lucky I am to work with and among artists and writers who will really dig in and bring so much heart and truth to their music - even if the tears come, even when the words are hard to sing. Thank you Tim, for always raising the bar and bringing me along for the ride.

1988

We got married in 1988. I was 19 and Gene was 21. Music was always part of my life but I didn’t find my place in music until the kids came along. I’d joke and say I went to the “University of having babies” when all my friends came home from college. I didn’t miss a thing.  I got to sit beside their beds and learn chords and find words to match them. The kids would fall asleep and I’d stay right there. Finding songs and trying to figure out who the hell I was. Music was an interstate for me, even in the years when I barely left the house and the songs stayed in the kitchen. This song is my way of thanking my younger self for trusting her heart, thanking Gene and the kids for taking the journey with me, and thanking the audience that followed.  I’d do it all again if I could. I got to write this one with my oldest, Brian, one of my greatest teachers.

I can’t even explain how much I wish this song wasn’t telling anyone’s story. But we all know it is. Wonder Drug is one of those songs that chased me around the house for a month before I finally wrote it down. The songs that chase me are few and far between and I consider them blessings even when they are this sad. I hope the take away is “run to love”. RUN TO LOVE.

I couldn’t miss the opportunity to record “Happy Children” acoustically with Dave Cobb. My dream for a song like this is always that it resonates on the simplest of levels, in kitchens (my fav), on front porches (my second fav) or at the end of a twin bed after a story when kids are falling asleep. I think we all wish this for each other and I certainly wish it for you. My sons @brianmckenna_ and @chris.mckenna (my cowriter) were in the room when we recorded and filmed this version, made it all that much sweeter! 

H&M by @andrialmckenna

1988 Deluxe edition is coming on 11/10 and you can pre-save through the link in my bio. These songs, as always with me, were written on acoustic guitars and sung over writing room sofas and across kitchen tables. I dreamed of Dave Cobb and the band bringing the electric side out of them as they did on 1988 - but I always knew I would want them represented in their original form. The way the balladeer in me hears all songs, just stripped down. I’m so thankful Dave was willing to go back with me and play them the way they land under my fingers as if they were just written all over again.

1988 Deluxe is out today and I’m so happy these acoustic versions are part of this project. Huge love to everybody who’s been journeying through these songs with me, singing with me, understanding what I’m trying to express, it’s such a blessing to see how much we’re all the same in music. I’ll always be your biggest fan. XO. LM

Another year in the books. Is it really 20 years we’ve been doing this thing? Four shows in two nights in the legendary room that has given me so much my entire career @clubpassim With the most amazing audiences. Friends, family, travelers, die harders, newbies, first daters and on and on. Thank you for making the time to spend this weekend with us. Thank you to this incredible band of mine @markerelli @paul.kochanski @sandstone67 and @smithtastic1970 (you’re part of the band now Matt because I don’t know how I would exist without you). Missing #jamieedwards and #alexhug who are touring elsewhere. Huge love and thanks to every audience member who made it to even a minute of one show over the years. Thank you for liking simple and sad songs. And thank you for giving me so much love! 🩵

Jan 10. 2024
Ten days in seems like a great time to wish you all a Happy New Year. Happy blank page, to the writers in us all. Happy new chord to the learners in us. Happy turn of phrase that opens up a million doors in us. Every morning I sit under this fiddle fig tree in our back room. It’s my favorite spot in the house for mornings. And this tree is the first green thing that I didn’t kill - so she’s taught me a lot. Mostly she reminds me to think, or better yet, not think so I can feel. Leaving the house today to start filling up the blank pages of this year and feeling so thankful that I get to be part of it all. Sending love to every single one of you (us).
